<p>This 1904 comic by Gustave Verbeek (click to enlarge) is a sort of visual palindrome &#8212; the first six panels are presented conventionally, and then they&#8217;re displayed again in reverse order and upside down to compose the story&#8217;s second half. Even the written messages change their meaning: <em>why big buns am mad u!</em> becomes <em>in pew we sung big hym</em>, and so on. Only the captions beneath the first panels are discarded in the second half.</p>
